      "section_id": "executive_summary",
      "title": "Executive Summary",
      "content": {
        "summary": "The June 2026 financial report reveals significant overspending in Engineering and Health Sciences departments, with Engineering exceeding its budget by $111,996 and Health Sciences by $92,859. The primary drivers include vendor payments for supplies and services, particularly from Professional Services Network and University Supply Cooperative, which contributed to the variance.",
        "key_findings": [
          "Engineering's actual expenses ($734,196) exceeded budget ($622,200) by $111,996, driven by vendor payments for supplies and services.",
          "Health Sciences' actual expenses ($658,959) exceeded budget ($566,100) by $92,859, with similar vendor payment patterns.",
          "Payroll variance for Health Sciences was $87,255, significantly higher than other departments, indicating potential misalignment in staffing or compensation planning.",
          "Student payment collections met targets with 100% paid status for Health Sciences in June 2026, suggesting no revenue shortfall."
        ],
        "root_causes": [
          "Unplanned vendor payments for supplies and services, particularly from Professional Services Network, contributed to overspending in both Engineering and Health Sciences.",
          "Health Sciences' payroll variance of $87,255 may stem from unexpected overtime or benefits costs not aligned with budgeted FTE headcount.",
          "Lack of real-time monitoring for vendor payment approvals may have allowed overspending to accumulate without early intervention."
        ],
        "confidence": 0.8,
        "analysis_status": "accepted"
